      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "## Make a List\n",
        "\n",
        "- Take the first 10 *unique* words from the file (in the order they appear) and store them in a list called `words`.  \n",
        "- Print the list.  \n",
        "- Print the 3rd and 7th items in the list.  \n",
        "\n",
        "Example:\n"
      ],
      "id": "39191eb0"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "words = [\"The\", \"Project\", \"Gutenberg\", \"EBook\", \"of\", \"William\", \"Shakespeare\", \"Complete\", \"by\", \"Shakespeare\"]\n",
        "print(words)\n",
        "print(words[2])   # 3rd item\n",
        "print(words[6])   # 7th item"
      ],
      "id": "995df4f0",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "## Make a Dictionary\n",
        "\n",
        "- Pick **3 of the words** from your `words` list.  \n",
        "- Use `.count()` to see how many times each appears in the text.  \n",
        "- Create a dictionary called `word_counts` that pairs each chosen word with its number.  \n",
        "\n",
        "Example:\n"
      ],
      "id": "485a4db1"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "word_counts = {\n",
        "    \"The\": text.count(\"The\"),\n",
        "    \"Project\": text.count(\"Project\"),\n",
        "    \"Shakespeare\": text.count(\"Shakespeare\")\n",
        "}\n",
        "print(word_counts)"
      ],
